A beautiful May evening, the love of my life and our prodigy, with the stars in alignment, all decided on something Mexican for dinner.
Previously, we had passed the Old Town Tortilla factory on a bicycle ride, and seeing the huge patio, thought this would be a good place for a quiet evening dinner.
Walking through the spanish-style arch into the courtyard of the tortilla factory, the charm and ambiance enveloped us and promised a perfect evening under the stars.
Then, we met the hostess.
Nope, she says.
No patio dining for at least another hour and a half, I've got a party of 100 that has reserved the patio.
But, she went on, you can have a seat at the bar, order an appetizer and I can see if I can squeeze you inside in a half an hour or so.
We gazed longingly at the gas torches flickering agains the sea of sombreros that filled the crowded patio, wishing we could be a part of that crowd.
Instead, we sat at the bar, and ordered margarita's and Nachos.
These items arrived quickly, narrowly edging out the hostess, who came to tell us our table was ready.
Ok, then, I guess we move into the house.
We were taken to a nice, open room just past the tortilla manufacturing station, and seated at a four-top next to a very loud party, with laughing and loud-talking puncturing the quiet spaces around.
We settled in to enjoy our drinks and chips.
$5 for a bowl of chips and salsa seems excessive, and the $10 that we paid to get them drenched in ground beef, fresh-sliced jalapeno, guacamole and cheese sauce seemed even more outrageous, especially given the taste.
It wasn't bad, but it wasn't ten-dollar good either.
Soon, our waittress arrived, took our order and delivered freshly-made black-bean tortillas with a rosemary butter - actually the most flavorful thing I enjoyed all evening.
I ordered a bowl of chile verde, the wife a tortilla soup, and the young one had "old-town tacos", the chicken variety.
The daughter said the strips of chicken were too spicy, but the wife enjoyed them, unlike her tortilla soup.
It was a deep red soup, with a drizzle of sour cream over it for pizazz.
She was not impressed positively.
Grab a handful of giant-cubed and steamed Idaho potatoes, a handful of boiled pork chunks, toss them in a bowl, pour a little greenish-looking sauce over them, fling a handful of cilantro leaves on it, and you've got the Tortilla Factory interpretation of Chile Verde.
If the waittress had told me it was "deconstructed", I might have ordered something else instead.
Chile Verde should be a thick, savory, spicy-hot stew of potatoes, pork, onion and chile that is simmered together until the flavors are absorbed by the potatoes, the pork is flaky-tender, and the chile heat sneaks up on you like a bandit in the night.
Unfortunately, the OTF chef missed this dish by so far, I'm hesitant to even describe it as Mexican food.
The steamed potatoes hadn't resided in the steamer long enough to take the crisp off, the pork was chewy and the sauce was just ho-hum.
The Old-Town Tortilla Factory probably rocks the socks off of anybody east of Texas, and that's probably where it should reside - where you find people that just don't know what real Mexican should taste like.

